# Vacuous Quantification — a silent false-pass counterpattern

Alloy's quantifiers follow standard logic: `∀x∈∅. P(x) ≡ true` and `∃x∈∅. P(x) ≡ false`.
This is correct semantics, but it interacts badly with the workflow

> write predicate → write `check` → solver says `assertion holds` → conclude property is proven

If the predicate quantifies universally over a set that can be **empty in the smallest
satisfying model**, the predicate is true at that case for trivial reasons and the `check`
will report `assertion holds` without anything being actually proven.

Read this file when:
- a `check` returns `assertion holds` on the first try and you didn't expect it to,
- a predicate uses `all` / `no` / `lone` over a comprehension involving `TO/prevs`,
  `TO/nexts`, `TO/last`, set difference, or a field that's allowed to be empty,
- the property you're checking is "eventually X" or "from some point on, never X" in a
  temporal model.

The Alloy language reference covers the semantics. It does **not** cover this as a
*modeling* trap. That's the gap this file fills.

---

## Pattern A — `all x: S | P` when `S` can be empty

### The bite

```alloy
// "there exists t such that for all later times, no bad event"
pred Converges {
  some t: T | all later: T - TO/prevs[t] - t | no Trace.bad[later]
}
```

At `t = TO/last`, the comprehension `T - TO/prevs[TO/last] - TO/last` is `∅`.
The inner `all later: ∅ | …` is vacuously true. The outer `some t` is therefore
satisfied at `t = TO/last` in **every** model — including ones where `Trace.bad` fires
forever. A `check { not Converges }` will say `assertion holds` and look like a real
impossibility result.

### Fixes

```alloy
// (1) Anchor at TO/last. Best when the model has a known finite horizon.
pred Converges {
  no Trace.bad[TO/last]
  and all later: T | TO/lt[TO/last, later] => no Trace.bad[later]
}

// (2) Exclude the boundary witness. Smallest edit.
pred Converges {
  some t: T | t != TO/last
    and all later: T - TO/prevs[t] - t | no Trace.bad[later]
}

// (3) Require the post-t set to be non-empty AND clean. Most defensive when
//     the emptiness of the post-set genuinely matters.
pred Converges {
  some t: T |
    (some later: T - TO/prevs[t] - t | true)
    and (no later: T - TO/prevs[t] - t | Trace.bad[later])
}
```

Pick (1) when the model has a finite horizon and the boundary is meaningful.
Pick (2) for the smallest edit. Pick (3) when the property is genuinely about a
non-empty tail.

---

## Pattern B — `lone x: S | P` is true when `|S| = 0`

`lone` means "at most one" — zero satisfies it. Combining `lone` with a set that can be
empty defines "at most one … or none," which is almost never what the author meant.

```alloy
// Says "at most one approver, OR no approvers at all." Often unintended.
fact { lone a: Order.approvers | a.role = Manager }

// If the intent is "exactly one approver of role Manager":
fact { one a: Order.approvers | a.role = Manager }
```

---

## Pattern C — `no x: S | P` is true when `S = ∅`

Symmetric to A. `no x: ∅ | P` is vacuously true.

```alloy
// True for any Foo with empty bar — including the all-empty model.
pred AllBarsClean { all f: Foo | no b: f.bar | b.broken }

// If the intent is "every Foo has bars AND none of them are broken":
pred AllBarsClean { all f: Foo | some f.bar and no b: f.bar | b.broken }
```

---

## Pattern D — Vacuous bound by quantified field

```alloy
sig Foo { bar: set Bar }
fact { all f: Foo | all b: f.bar | P[b] }   // SAT for any Foo with empty bar
```

Easy to miss when the spec allows `bar` to be empty. If `bar` is *required* to be
non-empty, state that explicitly:

```alloy
fact { all f: Foo | some f.bar }            // separate non-emptiness fact
fact { all f: Foo | all b: f.bar | P[b] }
```

Keeping the two facts separate keeps the intent legible and the failure modes
distinguishable when a counterexample arrives.

---

## Habit: cross-check before trusting `assertion holds`

When `check` returns `assertion holds`, ask three questions:

**1. Is there a universal quantifier whose domain can be empty in the smallest model?**

Scan the predicate for `all x: S | …`, `no x: S | …`, `lone x: S | …` where `S` is:
- a set comprehension built with `-`, `&`, `TO/prevs`, `TO/nexts`,
- a field `f` that the signature declares as `set` (i.e. `lone` or `set`, not `one`),
- the result of a `let` that can resolve to `∅`.

If yes, suspect vacuity before claiming a real proof.

**2. Run the negation at the boundary case.**

For Pattern A, add a targeted `run` that forces `t` to the boundary and asks for a
witness. If a witness exists trivially, the predicate is admitting vacuous models:

```alloy
run BoundaryWitness {
  some t: T | t = TO/last
    and all later: T - TO/prevs[t] - t | no Trace.bad[later]
} for 5
```

If this is SAT with `Trace.bad` populated arbitrarily, you've reproduced the trap.

**3. Use `expect 1` on the predicate's body to confirm a non-vacuous witness exists.**

```alloy
run ConvergesNonVacuous {
  some t: T | (some later: T - TO/prevs[t] - t | true)
    and Converges
} for 5 expect 1
```

If `check` says the property holds **and** this `run` returns UNSAT, the disagreement
flags the trap: the predicate is being satisfied only by models with an empty witness
set.

---

## Bottom line

- `∀x∈∅. P(x)` is true. Treat any `all` / `no` / `lone` over a derived set as suspect
  until you've verified the smallest model can't make that set empty.
- Don't conflate `lone` with `one`. `lone` admits zero.
- When a `check` passes on the first try and the property is non-trivial, pair it with
  a `run … expect 1` against the body to confirm a real witness exists.
- Boundary cases (`TO/last`, `TO/first`, empty fields) are where vacuity hides. Probe
  them explicitly.
